  "prompt": "How come Harry can see the Thestrals after his fourth year and not before that?",
  "response": "Harry Potter can see Thestrals after his fourth year because he witnesses the death of Cedric Diggory at the end of \"Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire.\" The ability to see Thestrals is tied to having seen and fully processed someone's death. Prior to Cedric's death, Harry had not fully processed or witnessed a death in a way that allowed him to see Thestrals.\n\nHere's a more detailed explanation:\n\n1. **Lily and James Potter's Death**: Harry was only a baby when his parents were killed by Voldemort. While this was a traumatic event, he was too young to fully comprehend and process their deaths, so it didn\u2019t grant him the ability to see Thestrals.\n\n2. **Quirrell's Death**: At the end of \"Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone,\" Harry causes Quirrell to die. However, Harry was unconscious when Quirrell actually died, so he didn\u2019t witness it directly.\n\n3. **Cedric Diggory's Death**: At the end of \"Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire,\" Harry witnesses Cedric's death at the hands of Peter Pettigrew, and he fully processes the event. This traumatic experience allows him to see Thestrals when he starts his fifth year at Hogwarts.\n\nThestrals are often misunderstood and considered dark creatures because they are associated with death, but they are gentle and intelligent beings. Their visibility to those who have seen death adds a layer of symbolism to the story, representing the impact of loss and the ability to see beyond the surface of things.",
